And I'm going to do this by breaking down the last three and a half years of my life into ten little stories for you all.

98
00:06:11,185 --> 00:06:14,688
So, this first story, let's take a look at this contradiction.

99
00:06:15,229 --> 00:06:18,452
We don't know what to make, but we know we need to make a lot of it.

100
00:06:19,212 --> 00:06:21,815
And at this point, at the beginning, you know, the project is a blank page.

101
00:06:22,415 --> 00:06:25,137
All we have is a premise, and we just have to figure out the rest.

102
00:06:25,758 --> 00:06:30,742
And this wouldn't have been so bad, were it not for the fact that everyone else was also sitting in front of a blank page.

103
00:06:31,363 --> 00:06:33,865
The story isn't written. We don't know how many quests there are going to be.

104
00:06:34,546 --> 00:06:37,387
We don't have any idea which characters people are going to need.

105
00:06:37,908 --> 00:06:40,550
And all the tools, you know, they're all still geared towards making kills in games.

106
00:06:40,610 --> 00:06:42,731
So these guys, they can't even make any quests.

107
00:06:42,751 --> 00:06:45,273
It's going to be a long time until we actually have any information to act on.

108
00:06:45,613 --> 00:06:46,934
But we can't just sit around and wait.

109
00:06:46,954 --> 00:06:48,895
I wanted to get some characters done,

110
00:06:49,656 --> 00:06:51,037
but I didn't want to do any thorough work.

111
00:06:51,757 --> 00:06:54,239
So for these early characters that we make to be useful,

112
00:06:55,019 --> 00:06:56,760
you know, what form do they need to take?

113
00:06:57,901 --> 00:06:58,482
Formless.

114
00:06:59,242 --> 00:06:59,763
Shapeless.

115
00:07:00,763 --> 00:07:01,404
Like water.

116
00:07:02,725 --> 00:07:03,665
You put water into a cup.

117
00:07:05,360 --> 00:07:08,822
It becomes the cup. You put water into a bottle, it becomes the bottle.

118
00:07:08,842 --> 00:07:11,604
You put it in a teapot, it becomes the teapot.

119
00:07:12,764 --> 00:07:15,025
So they had to be like water, you know.

120
00:07:15,666 --> 00:07:19,387
We didn't know exactly what shape hole they had to fill, so they had to fill any hole.

121
00:07:19,708 --> 00:07:22,789
Or put it another way, you know, we didn't know exactly how the characters would be used.

122
00:07:23,269 --> 00:07:25,891
So we'd need to start with the characters which were the most versatile.

123
00:07:27,070 --> 00:07:29,211
But normally this isn't always how things are done.

124
00:07:29,251 --> 00:07:33,032
You see, specific characters like the lead cast for example

125
00:07:33,052 --> 00:07:34,933
are some of the most important content you need to make

126
00:07:34,993 --> 00:07:37,094
and obviously it's like some of the more visible content,

127
00:07:37,114 --> 00:07:38,234
some of the most visible content.

128
00:07:38,934 --> 00:07:40,295
So it's often what people will start with.

129
00:07:40,815 --> 00:07:44,236
But you know, specific characters like these, this is risky.

130
00:07:44,776 --> 00:07:47,637
If you're doing a design which is geared to communicate

131
00:07:47,997 --> 00:07:48,898
one thing, one idea.

132
00:07:49,558 --> 00:07:50,398
What if things change?

133
00:07:51,859 --> 00:07:53,580
And what if things are cut?

134
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:55,461
That's just wasted time and effort.

135
00:07:56,281 --> 00:07:58,042
The more important someone is as well to the story,

136
00:07:58,302 --> 00:07:59,362
like these lead characters,

137
00:07:59,823 --> 00:08:01,303
the more likely it is they're going to change.

138
00:08:01,884 --> 00:08:03,304
Let's take Ross, for example.

139
00:08:03,384 --> 00:08:05,465
So Ross is Aloy's surrogate father.

140
00:08:05,945 --> 00:08:07,226
He's pivotal to the first act.

141
00:08:07,826 --> 00:08:09,227
He was part of the story back when

142
00:08:09,487 --> 00:08:10,668
they were still working out the premise.

143
00:08:11,553 --> 00:08:13,773
you'd think Ross, you know, he'd be a safe bet.

144
00:08:14,314 --> 00:08:15,354
But not at all.

145
00:08:15,714 --> 00:08:17,514
You see, as the story evolved, so did Ross.

146
00:08:18,275 --> 00:08:20,835
He mellows out a lot from this ax-wielding berserker

147
00:08:20,855 --> 00:08:21,436
you see on screen.

148
00:08:22,416 --> 00:08:24,096
And leaving what we know about Ross aside,

149
00:08:24,116 --> 00:08:25,137
you know, we don't really know anything about

150
00:08:25,157 --> 00:08:26,777
the culture that Ross comes from.

151
00:08:27,517 --> 00:08:28,998
You know, this is kind of important

152
00:08:29,018 --> 00:08:30,818
if you're doing a key character like Ross.

153
00:08:31,518 --> 00:08:34,279
Because he's individual, he's special.

154
00:08:34,919 --> 00:08:36,520
And if I don't know what the average person

155
00:08:36,540 --> 00:08:39,260
from Ross tribe looks like, you know,

156
00:08:39,300 --> 00:08:40,801
how do I know how to make this guy stand out?

157
00:08:42,282 --> 00:08:44,103
So instead of starting with individuals like Rost,

158
00:08:44,143 --> 00:08:45,303
we started with the generic guys.

159
00:08:45,964 --> 00:08:47,524
Generic is a bit of a dirty word.

160
00:08:48,685 --> 00:08:50,065
I say generic, you're probably thinking

161
00:08:50,506 --> 00:08:51,486
things looking the same,

162
00:08:51,586 --> 00:08:53,347
things looking boring like this poor guy.

163
00:08:54,587 --> 00:08:55,768
That's not really what generic means.

164
00:08:55,828 --> 00:08:58,149
It merely, it's merely the opposite of specific.

165
00:08:58,249 --> 00:08:59,449
It means versatile.

166
00:09:00,510 --> 00:09:01,790
So let's look at this from another angle.

167
00:09:02,525 --> 00:09:05,247
What characters did the design team need at the beginning of production?

168
00:09:06,027 --> 00:09:10,390
They don't really need specific characters like Ross because their ideas aren't yet that specific.

169
00:09:10,790 --> 00:09:11,991
They're still figuring things out.

170
00:09:12,351 --> 00:09:14,133
They need to have flexibility to change their minds.

171
00:09:14,613 --> 00:09:15,373
So we thought bigger.

172
00:09:15,413 --> 00:09:19,136
You know, instead of designing a person, we designed peoples.

173
00:09:19,296 --> 00:09:24,079
You know, we started with the cultures, the tribes, and we designed these guys as a unit.

174
00:09:24,119 --> 00:09:28,042
You know, we'd map out all the different kinds of character we thought we'd need in each tribe.

175
00:09:28,802 --> 00:09:30,543
And we call these key designs archetypes.

176
00:09:30,563 --> 00:09:31,943
You know, what you're looking at on the screen,

177
00:09:31,963 --> 00:09:34,144
these are the archetypes for the Kai tribe.

178
00:09:35,284 --> 00:09:36,164
But why do it this way?

179
00:09:36,885 --> 00:09:38,045
Well, the trick here is that,

180
00:09:38,285 --> 00:09:40,366
provided the tribe as a whole is versatile,

181
00:09:41,046 --> 00:09:43,047
individual archetypes can be less versatile

182
00:09:43,107 --> 00:09:44,627
if you're thinking about these guys in a unit.

183
00:09:45,027 --> 00:09:47,948
So that guard, you know, he's fairly limited in his uses,

184
00:09:48,368 --> 00:09:50,469
but that's okay, provided the rest of the population

185
00:09:50,889 --> 00:09:52,810
can cover what the quest team might need.

186
00:09:54,413 --> 00:09:58,897
But if we don't know anything, how do we go about identifying which of these archetypes to design?

187
00:09:59,718 --> 00:10:01,759
Well, we don't actually need that much to go off.

188
00:10:01,799 --> 00:10:06,484
We only need a few very basic assumptions like this from the writers in order to get started.

189
00:10:07,184 --> 00:10:09,486
I mean, we need a hell of a lot more to get finished,

190
00:10:10,047 --> 00:10:12,409
but we don't actually need all of this information to start.

191
00:10:13,659 --> 00:10:15,520
And with this little bit of information,

192
00:10:15,560 --> 00:10:17,000
you know, we can get stuck in,

193
00:10:17,020 --> 00:10:18,741
we can start designing those first archetypes.

194
00:10:19,241 --> 00:10:20,242
Once we have something to show,

195
00:10:20,262 --> 00:10:22,543
you know, we bounce things back and forth with the writers

196
00:10:22,703 --> 00:10:24,983
and we just continue that until we have all of these guys.

197
00:10:26,364 --> 00:10:27,464
And this worked out pretty great

198
00:10:27,925 --> 00:10:30,305
because whilst all the quests are their own little stories,

199
00:10:30,826 --> 00:10:31,906
these stories are taking place

200
00:10:31,946 --> 00:10:33,207
inside of an established world.

201
00:10:34,267 --> 00:10:35,547
And because we got started early,

202
00:10:35,587 --> 00:10:38,028
we got in on the ground floor with the writers

203
00:10:38,088 --> 00:10:39,489
whilst they're still doing this world building,

204
00:10:40,069 --> 00:10:41,450
these archetypes ended up being

205
00:10:41,470 --> 00:10:42,790
a part of that world building.

206
00:10:43,643 --> 00:10:46,646
So when the quest team, you know, when they needed to start nailing down

207
00:10:47,166 --> 00:10:48,847
what kind of characters they needed to use,

208
00:10:49,628 --> 00:10:52,931
they tended to be these kind of characters, you know, what a coincidence.

209
00:10:54,552 --> 00:10:57,915
And for every character with a name, we'd build a unique character from those generic parts,

210
00:10:57,935 --> 00:10:58,936
those generic archetypes.

211
00:10:59,857 --> 00:11:02,259
Many of our key characters, like Nil or like Petra,

212
00:11:02,819 --> 00:11:04,601
they just kept using these generic parts.

213
00:11:05,161 --> 00:11:07,423
Those parts, they just kind of fit the characters so well

214
00:11:07,844 --> 00:11:09,145
that we didn't need to change anything.

215
00:11:09,917 --> 00:11:13,701
But of course there were many, many other characters where that generic content wasn't good enough.

216
00:11:13,801 --> 00:11:17,124
There were some simple examples, you know, sometimes a character needs to look injured.

217
00:11:17,804 --> 00:11:22,328
But more importantly, we'd have a large number of important story characters

218
00:11:22,789 --> 00:11:25,171
where these kind of generic looks wouldn't fit their characterization.

219
00:11:25,511 --> 00:11:26,392
Let's go back to Rost.

