00:36:16,617 --> 00:36:20,541
These machines, you know, they're a threat, but they're also an opportunity.

730
00:36:21,201 --> 00:36:23,924
A low-tech culture is going to have all kinds of uses for the materials

731
00:36:23,944 --> 00:36:25,685
that they can strip off one of these damn machines.

732
00:36:26,684 --> 00:36:30,968
So this opens up a wealth of new opportunities to hit some of those key themes.

733
00:36:32,269 --> 00:36:37,475
You know, starting by mixing modern and natural through adding some of these robot materials to the characters.

734
00:36:37,675 --> 00:36:40,298
So it took a lot of exploration to get this right.

735
00:36:41,030 --> 00:36:44,293
This is one of our first attempts and these guys are really not very successful.

736
00:36:45,254 --> 00:36:48,356
Nothing really fit the character, there's no kind of practicality here.

737
00:36:49,097 --> 00:36:52,359
So we start thinking more about function, you know, why are these guys using the robot bits?

738
00:36:52,979 --> 00:36:55,621
And by this point, you know, the writers have established that the Nora,

739
00:36:55,641 --> 00:36:57,583
they don't really have any particular reverence for the robots.

740
00:36:58,243 --> 00:37:03,507
So these guys are going to be using them purely practically, as armor for instance.

741
00:37:04,470 --> 00:37:09,995
But working this out is tricky, okay, because if I make these robot pieces fit a person too well,

742
00:37:10,515 --> 00:37:13,578
you know, it looks too deliberate, it looks like they were designed for that person.

743
00:37:13,978 --> 00:37:18,182
You've basically designed a mech suit, you know, we need that contrast between the old and the new.

744
00:37:19,343 --> 00:37:22,165
But if the way that these things are applied, you know, it looks too improvised,

745
00:37:22,786 --> 00:37:25,868
it makes the Nora look like they're careless and messy,

746
00:37:26,449 --> 00:37:28,651
we're not kind of hitting that expert machine hunter note.

747
00:37:29,644 --> 00:37:30,864
So it took a lot of ideation.

748
00:37:31,305 --> 00:37:33,825
Eventually we solved this by striking the balance

749
00:37:33,865 --> 00:37:37,686
by using intricate configurations of these smaller plates.

750
00:37:39,407 --> 00:37:40,647
But we're still missing vibrancy

751
00:37:40,767 --> 00:37:42,248
because these natural materials,

752
00:37:43,148 --> 00:37:45,268
they're only providing a very, very limited palette.

753
00:37:46,589 --> 00:37:48,209
So we start thinking about maybe how we can use

754
00:37:48,229 --> 00:37:49,710
these robot parts to this effect.

755
00:37:50,810 --> 00:37:52,950
And we start by just taking small elements

756
00:37:52,990 --> 00:37:54,571
like bronze or gold connectors

757
00:37:55,051 --> 00:37:56,992
and use these things as accents, as jewelry.

758
00:37:58,339 --> 00:37:59,640
And then we also add in these cables,

759
00:38:00,380 --> 00:38:02,501
especially these really, really colourful anodised ones,

760
00:38:02,541 --> 00:38:04,021
you know, that have this kind of silvery luster.

761
00:38:05,962 --> 00:38:07,763
And then what we did, we interwoven these things

762
00:38:07,783 --> 00:38:09,683
with similar cables made from natural materials,

763
00:38:10,164 --> 00:38:11,944
and we get to this juxtaposition

764
00:38:11,964 --> 00:38:14,685
of the same shape language, but with different materials.

765
00:38:14,785 --> 00:38:16,326
You know, it helps to make the robot elements

766
00:38:16,366 --> 00:38:18,707
look less foreign, so we get our contrast,

767
00:38:19,147 --> 00:38:21,008
but in a way which isn't abrasive.

768
00:38:22,712 --> 00:38:28,875
And that's the really abbreviated version, but that's how we kind of worked out the main motifs for the Nora visual design.

769
00:38:29,495 --> 00:38:32,977
And because we approached this methodically, there were a lot fewer dead ends.

770
00:38:33,217 --> 00:38:36,438
We knew very quickly if something was working or if something was missing.

771
00:38:37,279 --> 00:38:40,860
And this methodical approach went beyond designing the individual tribes.

772
00:38:41,501 --> 00:38:45,883
Because in order to make the tribes distinct, before we designed any of them,

773
00:38:46,483 --> 00:38:49,084
we roughly mapped out what the core identity of each tribe would be

774
00:38:49,585 --> 00:38:51,085
and what the main force of shaping them would be.

775
00:38:51,808 --> 00:38:56,029
And by planning out things like location, climate, cultural development, technological

776
00:38:56,069 --> 00:39:00,530
sophistication, all these things in advance, we knew that even though we couldn't be sure

777
00:39:01,030 --> 00:39:03,631
exactly how they would end up, we knew that they would be distinct.

778
00:39:06,011 --> 00:39:08,412
So if art is subjective, how can you know what is right?

779
00:39:08,532 --> 00:39:12,532
Well, you don't need to know everything, but you do need to know what your work is really

780
00:39:12,592 --> 00:39:13,253
about, okay?

781
00:39:13,653 --> 00:39:18,554
And I don't mean in a mechanical way, like what the plot is, I mean the overarching themes,

782
00:39:18,894 --> 00:39:20,274
the ideas in the premise.

783
00:39:22,659 --> 00:39:24,920
Work through your designs one step at a time,

784
00:39:25,660 --> 00:39:27,981
making sure that your conclusions are internally consistent

785
00:39:28,542 --> 00:39:30,262
and logical, but more important,

786
00:39:31,203 --> 00:39:33,404
that these things embody the key themes

787
00:39:33,444 --> 00:39:34,884
and communicate them very clearly to the player.

788
00:39:36,545 --> 00:39:39,906
So yeah, once again, that was the super short version.

789
00:39:42,408 --> 00:39:44,729
And I kind of focused on the successes to save time.

790
00:39:46,368 --> 00:39:50,991
Which is pretty misleading, because I gave the impression that this was a lot easier than it was.

791
00:39:51,652 --> 00:39:53,593
And it really, really wasn't easy.

792
00:39:54,573 --> 00:39:57,335
So, when I show you that process as a story, it looks all fine and good,

793
00:39:57,355 --> 00:39:59,556
because you get a nice beginning, middle and end, you know?

794
00:40:00,057 --> 00:40:02,318
But being in the middle of that is something else entirely.

795
00:40:02,918 --> 00:40:06,401
It was frustrating and difficult, and at times I thought it was never going to end.

796
00:40:07,481 --> 00:40:09,803
We generated so much material, I couldn't possibly show it to you all.

797
00:40:09,823 --> 00:40:11,424
This is just like a small selection I grabbed.

798
00:40:11,444 --> 00:40:13,965
But you see, in reality...

799
00:40:15,180 --> 00:40:18,905
Design is about trying to find your way to some kind of end goal, because you often don't

800
00:40:18,925 --> 00:40:20,367
know what that end goal is until you reach it.

801
00:40:21,368 --> 00:40:23,952
And even then, sometimes when you do reach it, you're still not sure.

802
00:40:25,313 --> 00:40:28,978
So our process, it's less of a roadmap and it's more of an evolutionary tree.

803
00:40:30,185 --> 00:40:32,966
Normally we have some kind of jumping off point, like those assumptions.

804
00:40:33,646 --> 00:40:35,126
So we generate some ideas, okay?

805
00:40:35,407 --> 00:40:37,047
And our concept guides, they're great.

806
00:40:37,287 --> 00:40:38,748
So all of these ideas, they're great.

807
00:40:39,328 --> 00:40:41,669
But we have to choose what to commit to.

808
00:40:41,709 --> 00:40:43,129
You know, we have to start making decisions.

809
00:40:43,689 --> 00:40:45,510
Again, not picking between good or bad ideas.

810
00:40:45,550 --> 00:40:50,031
We're selecting ideas on how effective they are at encompassing that original intent,

811
00:40:50,792 --> 00:40:53,933
as well as how complementary they are with the other decisions that we've made.

812
00:40:54,911 --> 00:40:56,512
And this process just basically continues.

813
00:40:56,752 --> 00:41:02,216
We ideate, we make decisions, we ideate, we make decisions,

814
00:41:02,336 --> 00:41:04,457
and then at some point you just have to kind of stop

815
00:41:05,158 --> 00:41:05,778
when you're feeling it.

816
00:41:07,559 --> 00:41:09,441
But committing to things, super important,

817
00:41:09,521 --> 00:41:11,382
because it creates this positive feedback loop.

818
00:41:12,082 --> 00:41:13,143
The more decisions you make,

819
00:41:13,523 --> 00:41:15,144
the easier it is to make even more decisions,

820
00:41:15,184 --> 00:41:17,126
because you can base them on the decisions you've just made.

821
00:41:17,826 --> 00:41:19,207
You get this snowballing phenomenon

822
00:41:19,507 --> 00:41:21,168
called the cone of uncertainty.

823
00:41:22,634 --> 00:41:25,216
Which is basically that as you make decisions over time,

824
00:41:25,616 --> 00:41:27,238
the number of possibilities decrease,

825
00:41:27,858 --> 00:41:29,459
which means that certainty increases,

826
00:41:30,140 --> 00:41:32,502
and then it's easier to make progress and do useful work.

827
00:41:33,502 --> 00:41:36,104
And on the beginning of a new IP like Horizon,

828
00:41:36,364 --> 00:41:38,246
those possibilities, they're endless.

829
00:41:38,586 --> 00:41:39,607
We could have done anything.

830
00:41:40,688 --> 00:41:42,809
So it's very easy to feel lost and hopeless,

831
00:41:43,550 --> 00:41:45,671
and it felt a lot more comfortable to play it safe

832
00:41:45,732 --> 00:41:46,792
and just not commit to anything.

833
00:41:47,313 --> 00:41:49,334
But I just had to ignore this and just start making decisions

834
00:41:49,354 --> 00:41:51,056
because it's literally the only way to make progress.

835
00:41:52,518 --> 00:41:56,362
But those decisions, they can be pretty hard because it often feels like you're throwing

836
00:41:56,402 --> 00:41:57,683
away great ideas.

837
00:41:58,384 --> 00:42:03,770
This guy, he's a tech priest from when the guys were just working on the premise.

838
00:42:04,651 --> 00:42:08,434
The story changed a lot and this guy got cut because he no longer fit.

839
00:42:09,035 --> 00:42:16,358
But his design was so strong and it had so many great ideas that just some of the themes and ideas just kept re-emerging.

840
00:42:16,378 --> 00:42:19,399
You know, the robes and the colours, they influenced a very similar Mesa priest.

841
00:42:19,939 --> 00:42:23,720
The Paron logo that's stitched on his sleeves, you know, we adapted this for the Eclipse cult

842
00:42:24,241 --> 00:42:26,562
and this iconography just made a hell of a lot more sense for these guys.

843
00:42:27,242 --> 00:42:28,922
You know, and the cable stitched into his flesh.

844
00:42:29,403 --> 00:42:31,403
You know, we incorporated these into the Banuk shamans

845
00:42:32,024 --> 00:42:36,165
and the writing team then, you know, imbued them with a lot more meaning and they became a lot more important.

846
00:42:37,077 --> 00:42:41,458
I didn't need to worry because if those ideas were really strong, they persisted,

847
00:42:42,558 --> 00:42:45,099
a good idea stays with you, it gets stuck up here.

848
00:42:46,959 --> 00:42:48,820
It's impossible to unsee things, okay?

849
00:42:49,360 --> 00:42:51,180
So this is a bunch of random noise, yeah?

850
00:42:51,200 --> 00:42:55,362
Okay, and now you see a dog, okay?

851
00:42:56,162 --> 00:42:58,883
And now you will see the dog whenever you see this picture.

852
00:42:58,963 --> 00:43:00,763
It's now stuck in your subconscious forever.

853
00:43:01,323 --> 00:43:04,284
I could show you this image again in five years and you will still see the dog.

854
00:43:06,253 --> 00:43:08,975
So how can you get to the end if you don't know the way?

855
00:43:09,935 --> 00:43:12,797
Well, don't despair if it feels like you're not making progress

856
00:43:12,957 --> 00:43:15,299
because the worst thing you can do is be too careful.

857
00:43:16,139 --> 00:43:18,301
The best way to crawl through that cone of uncertainty

858
00:43:18,781 --> 00:43:21,683
is to start making decisions, start committing to things,

859
00:43:22,684 --> 00:43:24,845
and don't stress out about cutting things.

860
00:43:24,865 --> 00:43:27,247
You know, if something is good and it gets cut,

861
00:43:28,047 --> 00:43:29,768
it will find its place sooner rather than later.

862
00:43:32,426 --> 00:43:35,367
So making those decisions, that's pretty important.

863
00:43:36,668 --> 00:43:38,208
But you need to be sure you're making those decisions

864
00:43:38,248 --> 00:43:39,109
for the right reasons.

865
00:43:40,709 --> 00:43:41,970
I'm not making those decisions on my own,

866
00:43:42,010 --> 00:43:43,310
we're making things for other people to use,

867
00:43:43,330 --> 00:43:44,451
so there are a lot of stakeholders

868
00:43:44,751 --> 00:43:45,872
from lots of different disciplines.

869
00:43:47,168 --> 00:43:49,890
And this means that we're getting feedback from people who don't always have an art background.

870
00:43:50,331 --> 00:43:54,434
These guys, they don't always have the artistic vocabulary to verbalize their feedback clearly.

871
00:43:54,454 --> 00:43:58,457
You know, they're not always able to do things like separate presentation from design.

872
00:43:59,457 --> 00:44:04,881
But turning this inward, as artists, we're not exactly objective about our own work either.

873
00:44:06,543 --> 00:44:11,326
Everyone has their blind spots. Everyone can be swayed by quality of finish or taste rather than content.

874
00:44:12,267 --> 00:44:18,454
So, as an example, we present lineups like this, even though these things are just about

875
00:44:18,514 --> 00:44:22,639
presenting costume design and getting feedback on costume design, people were getting swayed

876
00:44:22,659 --> 00:44:28,546
by things like gesture, facial expression, even silly things like the order in which

877
00:44:28,586 --> 00:44:29,567
things were presented.

878
00:44:31,310 --> 00:44:34,913
We'd talk about this beforehand, and people would make a conscious effort not to be swayed.

879
00:44:35,313 --> 00:44:37,655
But it's really hard, practically impossible even.

880
00:44:38,576 --> 00:44:41,238
The feedback that we were getting was just less useful as a result.

881
00:44:42,298 --> 00:44:47,683
So in a misguided attempt to address this issue, I shifted us to lineups of identical

882
00:44:47,703 --> 00:44:49,804
poses and models, so the only difference was costume.

883
00:44:50,845 --> 00:44:56,009
It didn't really work like I thought it would, because before, if someone didn't like a pose

884
00:44:56,069 --> 00:44:59,011
or something, they didn't like that one specific variant.

885
00:44:59,552 --> 00:45:03,917
But now, if someone doesn't like the pose or the face, they don't like any of them.

886
00:45:05,725 --> 00:45:07,726
So those contextual clues like gesture,

887
00:45:08,386 --> 00:45:10,107
they're irrelevant to the costume design, yes,

888
00:45:10,407 --> 00:45:11,247
but it's not just fluff.

889
00:45:11,267 --> 00:45:13,608
They're communicating vital aspects of the character.

890
00:45:14,169 --> 00:45:16,329
So now what we do is we go wide representation

891
00:45:16,349 --> 00:45:18,430
to begin with, and then we standardize

892
00:45:18,590 --> 00:45:20,731
as the design is closing, as we're getting towards the end.

893
00:45:21,432 --> 00:45:23,252
And sometimes, like this example on screen,

894
00:45:23,773 --> 00:45:25,954
where we draw the same illustration, the same design,

895
00:45:26,094 --> 00:45:27,694
under different conditions to A-B test

896
00:45:27,754 --> 00:45:29,455
and work out exactly what it is people like

897
00:45:29,495 --> 00:45:31,276
about a very specific illustration.

898
00:45:32,674 --> 00:45:34,917
You know, you can't defeat bias with brute force.

899
00:45:35,398 --> 00:45:36,700
It's just something you have to account for.

900
00:45:38,182 --> 00:45:39,504
And another thing you have to account for

901
00:45:39,524 --> 00:45:41,026
is people's expectations.

902
00:45:41,327 --> 00:45:43,850
So before someone sees your work,

903
00:45:44,251 --> 00:45:45,873
they will have their own mental image

904
00:45:46,194 --> 00:45:47,035
of what they expect to see.

905
00:45:47,915 --> 00:45:50,818
And if what you show is different from those expectations,

906
00:45:51,619 --> 00:45:53,240
even if it's appropriate and even if it's good,

907
00:45:53,740 --> 00:45:55,482
it can trigger an adverse reaction.

908
00:45:56,823 --> 00:45:59,025
So this is the first design for Silence.

909
00:45:59,185 --> 00:46:00,807
So for people who don't know,

910
00:46:01,207 --> 00:46:04,890
Silence is this kind of morally dubious genius badass.

911
00:46:06,291 --> 00:46:07,813
He was first described to us by the writers

912
00:46:07,873 --> 00:46:09,334
as this kind of technological wizard,

913
00:46:09,914 --> 00:46:11,636
but he's also an awesome hunter.

914
00:46:11,936 --> 00:46:13,638
He has no problems taking down machines.

915
00:46:14,338 --> 00:46:18,641
So I see this first concept, you know, and it's awesome.

916
00:46:18,821 --> 00:46:20,762
It nails who I think Silence is.

917
00:46:20,922 --> 00:46:22,963
And the concept team, they also think they've nailed it in one.

918
00:46:23,404 --> 00:46:24,684
So we're really enthusiastic.

919
00:46:24,925 --> 00:46:27,086
We go show it to the writers, and they like it.

920
00:46:28,487 --> 00:46:30,488
But they don't really see him as Silence

921
00:46:31,348 --> 00:46:33,710
because it doesn't really meet that wizard description that they gave us.

922
00:46:34,550 --> 00:46:38,674
So, but no worries, you know, we discuss our expectations and we do a bit more exploration.

923
00:46:39,054 --> 00:46:41,876
And we're not really sure on this wizard thing, so we start subtle, you know.

924
00:46:42,376 --> 00:46:45,299
We show them this, they're not really feeling it, you know.

925
00:46:45,359 --> 00:46:47,400
It's not really as striking as that first design,

926
00:46:48,161 --> 00:46:50,603
and it's not really as strong on that wizard note as it should be.

927
00:46:51,704 --> 00:46:53,685
So we think, okay, we're being a bit uncompromising.

928
00:46:54,045 --> 00:46:58,629
Let's pull the wizard slider to max, thinking that this is what silence needs to be.

929
00:46:59,530 --> 00:47:01,851
But unexpectedly, they don't like this one any better.

930
00:47:02,777 --> 00:47:07,158
And every time we talk about these concepts, everyone's always doing it in the context

931
00:47:07,198 --> 00:47:08,138
of that first concept.

932
00:47:08,198 --> 00:47:10,499
It was just like, it left such a strong impression.

933
00:47:11,139 --> 00:47:13,239
It essentially just pulled everything else into its orbit.

934
00:47:13,919 --> 00:47:17,320
And it wasn't so much that it was wrong, it was just that it wasn't really what they had

935
00:47:17,360 --> 00:47:17,900
in mind.

936
00:47:18,381 --> 00:47:19,721
And it just took a bit of adjusting to.

937
00:47:20,481 --> 00:47:24,622
And ultimately what we ended up shipping with was something pretty close to that first concept.

938
00:47:26,105 --> 00:47:28,626
Now mind, those explorations, they weren't wasted time.

939
00:47:28,666 --> 00:47:30,567
You see, we incorporated a lot of the features

940
00:47:30,947 --> 00:47:32,648
from those ideations into the final,

941
00:47:33,529 --> 00:47:35,190
but it just meant that we kind of got there

942
00:47:35,210 --> 00:47:36,430
in a fairly roundabout way.

943
00:47:36,971 --> 00:47:38,852
So now what I do is I try and make sure

944
00:47:38,872 --> 00:47:40,753
that every design has a bit of breathing room

945
00:47:41,293 --> 00:47:42,874
by making sure that people see designs

946
00:47:43,294 --> 00:47:45,616
long before they're asked to cast judgment on them.

947
00:47:46,356 --> 00:47:48,157
You know, I try and do this out of context

948
00:47:48,677 --> 00:47:50,478
so it doesn't feel like I'm soliciting their opinion

949
00:47:50,819 --> 00:47:51,559
that very second.

950
00:47:52,770 --> 00:47:56,312
And this is like silly, simple things like, you know, print them out big and stick them around the office,

951
00:47:56,832 --> 00:47:58,513
slip them into random emails and meetings.

952
00:47:59,313 --> 00:48:05,776
And this sounds a little bit manipulative, but it's not really, because if someone really, really doesn't like a design,

953
00:48:06,196 --> 00:48:07,897
a bit of time isn't going to help, you know.

954
00:48:09,197 --> 00:48:14,499
If you're doing something original and with something which is sometimes a little bit weird, like Horizon is,

955
00:48:15,240 --> 00:48:19,681
in order to give a design a chance to be properly appraised, you know, appraised objectively,

956
00:48:20,505 --> 00:48:22,106
it needs a bit of a climatization time.

957
00:48:22,866 --> 00:48:25,687
And I found that if you do this,

958
00:48:25,807 --> 00:48:27,708
the more original, the more distinctive designs,

959
00:48:28,228 --> 00:48:29,809
they're the ones that consistently win out.

960
00:48:31,310 --> 00:48:34,111
So how can you keep that feedback objective?

961
00:48:34,711 --> 00:48:36,672
Well, be aware that your design work

962
00:48:36,732 --> 00:48:37,632
is judged holistically,

963
00:48:37,652 --> 00:48:39,153
not just that one thing you want to focus on.

964
00:48:39,945 --> 00:48:42,507
Be aware that everyone brings their expectations and preconceptions.

965
00:48:43,548 --> 00:48:44,749
So give your work room to breathe.

966
00:48:44,769 --> 00:48:47,832
You know, in my experience, the more radical, the more unexpected the design,

967
00:48:48,272 --> 00:48:51,415
the more acclimatization people need to see it objectively.

968
00:48:55,698 --> 00:48:58,120
So we're going to stick with this theme of psychological blind spots.

969
00:48:58,801 --> 00:49:01,783
So here's a story about a time that I fell into that coma failing,

970
00:49:02,744 --> 00:49:05,946
getting excited about the process whilst losing sight of the end result.

971
00:49:06,607 --> 00:49:09,149
You know, for where I'm from, we call this being too clever by half.

972
00:49:10,886 --> 00:49:13,227
So now we have a whole bunch of distinctive,

973
00:49:13,247 --> 00:49:15,228
diverse designs, you know, the concept's ready to go.

974
00:49:15,709 --> 00:49:16,449
Now the problem is like,

975
00:49:16,489 --> 00:49:18,130
how do we make all this stuff cost effectively?

976
00:49:18,150 --> 00:49:19,191
You know, how do we make these things,

977
00:49:19,311 --> 00:49:21,452
these characters as efficiently as possible?

978
00:49:22,253 --> 00:49:24,774
And modular construction is a fairly obvious way to go.

979
00:49:24,794 --> 00:49:27,896
So, you know, we start with this Lego approach.

980
00:49:27,956 --> 00:49:31,098
You know, we build huge libraries of small pieces,

981
00:49:31,118 --> 00:49:32,659
you know, discrete chunks of the character

982
00:49:33,000 --> 00:49:34,460
which are individually versatile.

983
00:49:35,661 --> 00:49:36,822
And then we just start recombining these

984
00:49:36,842 --> 00:49:37,863
to make many different variants.

985
00:49:38,463 --> 00:49:39,944
And on paper, this looks really promising.

986
00:49:40,689 --> 00:49:43,992
But when you transition to 3D, the reality is pretty different.

987
00:49:44,572 --> 00:49:47,735
Because our designs, they use a lot of layering and a lot of overlap.

988
00:49:49,076 --> 00:49:51,177
This makes it really difficult for these pieces to work together

989
00:49:51,538 --> 00:49:53,699
without intersections or without reading complications.

990
00:49:54,260 --> 00:49:56,161
So in order to make these things work together,

991
00:49:56,582 --> 00:49:58,703
we were constantly making design compromises

992
00:49:59,204 --> 00:50:01,125
in order to make things physically fit.

993
00:50:01,986 --> 00:50:05,729
And a good design, it can tolerate a little bit of compromise.

994
00:50:06,375 --> 00:50:10,617
But the difficulty with these modular systems is that every time you add a new piece,

995
00:50:11,137 --> 00:50:14,598
the number of these interdependencies increase exponentially.

996
00:50:15,119 --> 00:50:19,881
So each of these lines represents a dependency between these pieces,

997
00:50:20,741 --> 00:50:24,763
and the more of these dependencies you have, the more compromises you are going to need to make.

998
00:50:25,843 --> 00:50:29,825
And this looks like a lot, but this is really just like three sets of pieces.

999
00:50:30,305 --> 00:50:33,727
This complexity, it scales exponentially, you know, here's 10 sets of pieces.

1000
00:50:35,479 --> 00:50:37,001
This only gets worse and worse, okay?

1001
00:50:37,702 --> 00:50:40,065
So now, you know, I can only think of two ways to make this work.

1002
00:50:40,586 --> 00:50:44,310
Option one is we do like hard rules on piece design, we settle on standardized,

1003
00:50:44,711 --> 00:50:47,374
very, very similar forms, very, very similar volumes.

1004
00:50:47,715 --> 00:50:50,558
But this kind of defeats our point because everything is just going to end up looking the same.

1005
00:50:51,692 --> 00:50:55,534
Option two is like we try and defeat this with cleverness, you know, we kind of create

1006
00:50:55,554 --> 00:50:58,176
some tool that does some kind of procedural fitting system.

1007
00:50:58,837 --> 00:51:01,539
But the trick is like these things, they come with a lot of management overhead.

1008
00:51:01,839 --> 00:51:05,222
They require a lot of time to use and maintain.

1009
00:51:05,742 --> 00:51:07,903
And this is time that I could be spending making more characters.

1010
00:51:08,964 --> 00:51:14,066
And really the most that these systems can do is just kind of clumsily warp and fit pieces together

1011
00:51:14,846 --> 00:51:18,868
and that's not really a compromise I was willing to make because I would lose all of these bulges,

1012
00:51:18,968 --> 00:51:23,530
compression folds, you know, these are important descriptive details that really make these

1013
00:51:23,570 --> 00:51:30,633
materials feel real. So to cut a long story short, the problem wasn't a modular construction problem,

1014
00:51:31,353 --> 00:51:33,674
it was a damn problem. I was being too clever by half.

1015
00:51:34,339 --> 00:51:38,023
I've gotten so enamored with the potential of this modular process that I essentially

1016
00:51:38,043 --> 00:51:42,547
just lost sight of the outcome, which was simply to make as much variation as efficiently

1017
00:51:42,587 --> 00:51:43,047
as possible.

1018
00:51:44,148 --> 00:51:50,534
So in reality that's dead simple, because not every part of a design adds value equally.

1019
00:51:51,892 --> 00:51:54,633
So now what we do is we just look at a set of archetypical designs like this.

1020
00:51:55,173 --> 00:51:56,994
We identify the elements which are most distinct,

1021
00:51:57,354 --> 00:52:00,275
have the most visual variation from design to design,

1022
00:52:00,995 --> 00:52:03,495
and then conversely we identify the bits which have the least variation,

1023
00:52:04,196 --> 00:52:05,736
which are most similar from character to character,

1024
00:52:06,236 --> 00:52:08,497
and then we break them up and we make lots of that first category,

1025
00:52:08,577 --> 00:52:11,158
and then we make fewer or one of the second.

1026
00:52:13,058 --> 00:52:19,581
So we have bigger pieces, they have less interdependencies, and this worked out a hell of a lot better.

1027
00:52:20,101 --> 00:52:24,343
So we can't make quite as many different variants with this set as I could in the earlier example,

1028
00:52:24,744 --> 00:52:28,325
but the variants that I can make are substantially more different looking from one another,

1029
00:52:28,765 --> 00:52:33,007
but even more importantly, because I know interdependencies across these archetypical characters,

1030
00:52:33,427 --> 00:52:35,688
I can make every archetype look very different from one another.

1031
00:52:38,312 --> 00:52:39,674
So how can you avoid being too clever?

1032
00:52:40,135 --> 00:52:41,877
Well, don't lose sight of your objective.

1033
00:52:42,498 --> 00:52:43,840
Focus on what you're trying to achieve.

1034
00:52:44,200 --> 00:52:46,544
Don't get seduced by cleverness for its own sake.

1035
00:52:47,805 --> 00:52:49,828
Make sure it's the problem that's leading the process,

1036
00:52:49,928 --> 00:52:50,850
not the solution.

1037
00:52:52,532 --> 00:52:54,895
So these techniques, they helped us make more content.

1038
00:52:57,327 --> 00:52:59,970
But even then the scope of the game is still hilariously overwhelming.

1039
00:53:00,650 --> 00:53:04,234
And Guerrilla is not exactly a small studio, you know, Horizon was about 200 people.

1040
00:53:04,774 --> 00:53:09,438
But we like to pretend and we try and keep a small studio mindset.

1041
00:53:10,405 --> 00:53:12,648
We like having things like direct lines of communication.

1042
00:53:13,068 --> 00:53:14,610
We like having an open environment

1043
00:53:14,650 --> 00:53:16,292
where everyone can be criticized.

1044
00:53:16,973 --> 00:53:19,456
But with every single extra person you add to a team,

1045
00:53:19,976 --> 00:53:22,659
collaboration becomes harder, it becomes more formal.

1046
00:53:23,701 --> 00:53:25,763
So what we did with the Horizon Character team

1047
00:53:25,783 --> 00:53:26,984
was keep it deliberately small.

1048
00:53:27,325 --> 00:53:29,868
We only had four full-time artists and two contractors.

1049
00:53:31,222 --> 00:53:35,164
So this of course means that we relied a lot on outsourcing.

1050
00:53:36,485 --> 00:53:39,827
And I could talk all day about how to outsource effectively, but I have three minutes,

1051
00:53:40,328 --> 00:53:42,769
so I'm going to focus on, you know, perhaps the most important thing.

1052
00:53:44,230 --> 00:53:47,152
To outsource effectively, you need to outsource the right things.

1053
00:53:47,753 --> 00:53:50,154
And the right things are not always the most obvious things.

1054
00:53:50,174 --> 00:53:52,076
They're not always the things that you might want to outsource.

1055
00:53:52,930 --> 00:53:57,652
But if you want to make a lot of stuff with a small team, you need to be constantly asking yourself on every task, you know, can we outsource this?

1056
00:53:58,373 --> 00:54:03,735
And the trick to untangling this question is to consider where it is that your studio really is adding the value, okay?

1057
00:54:04,215 --> 00:54:06,316
Because those are the things that you shouldn't be outsourcing.

1058
00:54:07,416 --> 00:54:10,277
And at Grimmel Games, you know, we're a game developer.

1059
00:54:11,158 --> 00:54:14,399
We're not a creative commune, we're not an art school, we're not a model factory.

1060
00:54:14,979 --> 00:54:15,820
We're making video games.

1061
00:54:16,712 --> 00:54:18,993
And the meat of the game is the player experience,

1062
00:54:19,013 --> 00:54:21,235
where the storytelling, the gameplay, the technology,

1063
00:54:21,275 --> 00:54:23,496
the visuals, where all of this stuff comes together.

1064
00:54:23,516 --> 00:54:25,837
You know, this is what people remember.

1065
00:54:25,857 --> 00:54:27,558
This is what gives the game its identity.

1066
00:54:28,318 --> 00:54:29,439
This is what we need to own.

1067
00:54:29,479 --> 00:54:31,740
This is where we really are adding the value.

1068
00:54:32,340 --> 00:54:35,142
And everything else is essentially details and execution.

1069
00:54:36,223 --> 00:54:38,144
So, game meshes, can we outsource this?

1070
00:54:38,804 --> 00:54:40,205
Well, doing a good game mesh, yeah,

1071
00:54:40,346 --> 00:54:43,067
it requires skill, it requires practice and talent, okay?

1072
00:54:43,688 --> 00:54:45,449
But the outcome is relatively objective

1073
00:54:45,509 --> 00:54:46,930
and fairly easy to communicate.

1074
00:54:46,950 --> 00:54:48,171
It needs to look good,

1075
00:54:48,191 --> 00:54:49,912
it needs to meet the performance requirements.

1076
00:54:51,153 --> 00:54:52,694
This means it's super easy to train,

1077
00:54:53,235 --> 00:54:55,837
it's easy to brief, it's easy to review.

1078
00:54:57,057 --> 00:54:59,579
But they're super time consuming to do well, you know?

1079
00:54:59,699 --> 00:55:01,120
So what value are you adding?

1080
00:55:01,510 --> 00:55:03,231
by like tying up your internal stuff,

1081
00:55:03,931 --> 00:55:04,911
making these game meshes.

1082
00:55:05,631 --> 00:55:06,852
Let's look at this from another angle.

1083
00:55:07,432 --> 00:55:09,392
Here's a workflow from the perspective

1084
00:55:09,432 --> 00:55:10,893
of the person making the game mesh.

1085
00:55:11,533 --> 00:55:13,173
So you see someone is handing them a high poly,

1086
00:55:13,593 --> 00:55:15,074
and then in the middle they do their thing,

1087
00:55:15,434 --> 00:55:16,854
and they hand their stuff off to like,

1088
00:55:16,934 --> 00:55:18,095
whoever's doing the UVs, okay?

1089
00:55:18,635 --> 00:55:20,915
So this work is just flowing in one direction.

1090
00:55:21,959 --> 00:55:26,201
You know, there are clear endpoints, clear success criteria for every single handover.

1091
00:55:26,742 --> 00:55:28,963
This is not exactly a collaborative process.

1092
00:55:29,303 --> 00:55:32,405
These guys need to cooperate, they need to make sure their shit is getting done, take

1093
00:55:32,425 --> 00:55:35,647
any special notes, but their interactions aren't really adding a lot to the outcome.

1094
00:55:35,828 --> 00:55:38,249
You know, this is the difference between cooperation and collaboration.

1095
00:55:38,649 --> 00:55:43,132
Collaboration is where those interactions make a team greater than the sum of its parts.

1096
00:55:44,113 --> 00:55:47,735
So there's no real reason to have these three guys sit next to each other because they can

1097
00:55:47,755 --> 00:55:51,638
do their job more or less equally the same as if they were hundreds of miles apart.

1098
00:55:53,045 --> 00:55:55,286
Let's compare this to an example of something we did with the studio,

1099
00:55:55,306 --> 00:55:59,588
you know, Aloy's hair, can we outsource this? No.

1100
00:56:00,769 --> 00:56:03,870
Because this is not just an asset we can shuffle around, it's an R&D project,

1101
00:56:04,251 --> 00:56:05,391
it spans multiple disciplines,

1102
00:56:05,731 --> 00:56:07,872
and everyone is adding something different to the process.

1103
00:56:08,493 --> 00:56:10,914
The flow is not one-dimensional and predictable,

1104
00:56:11,274 --> 00:56:14,475
it's back and forth, it has dead ends, it has eureka moments.

1105
00:56:15,616 --> 00:56:18,217
And a project like this benefits from people working closely together,

1106
00:56:18,237 --> 00:56:19,978
you know, people who know each other well enough

1107
00:56:19,998 --> 00:56:22,039
that they can have a passionate argument about something.

1108
00:56:22,493 --> 00:56:23,735
without things getting too personal.

1109
00:56:25,396 --> 00:56:27,638
So Aloy's hair is important.

1110
00:56:27,918 --> 00:56:30,140
Anything Aloy related is important.

1111
00:56:31,000 --> 00:56:32,742
Because of course, she's one of the pillars of the game.

1112
00:56:32,762 --> 00:56:34,764
But as important as she was,

1113
00:56:34,824 --> 00:56:37,005
it didn't mean that we had to do every single facet of her

1114
00:56:37,446 --> 00:56:38,286
inside the studio.

1115
00:56:39,327 --> 00:56:41,069
And I talked about our speed model process before.

1116
00:56:41,449 --> 00:56:42,470
So inside the studio,

1117
00:56:42,510 --> 00:56:44,632
we spend a lot of time working at Aloy in 3D.

1118
00:56:44,672 --> 00:56:46,393
We get her in the game, we get feedback,

1119
00:56:46,413 --> 00:56:47,374
we see how she feels to play.

1120
00:56:48,024 --> 00:56:50,345
And after an extremely long and collaborative process,

1121
00:56:50,385 --> 00:56:52,046
we feel like we've resolved the design,

1122
00:56:52,367 --> 00:56:54,508
the proportions are good, the design elements are working,

1123
00:56:54,948 --> 00:56:56,169
you know, she's nice and readable.

1124
00:56:56,689 --> 00:56:58,590
We're ready to do this kind of final high poly,

1125
00:56:58,650 --> 00:57:00,931
add in all that detail, material expression,

1126
00:57:00,952 --> 00:57:02,973
you know, everything she needs to feel believable.

1127
00:57:03,693 --> 00:57:04,854
Can we outsource this? Yes.

1128
00:57:05,254 --> 00:57:06,535
And at this point, we hand it over

1129
00:57:06,575 --> 00:57:07,575
to one of our skilled friends,

1130
00:57:08,316 --> 00:57:10,357
because whilst this is extremely important,

1131
00:57:10,837 --> 00:57:12,038
things like material expression,

1132
00:57:12,438 --> 00:57:13,979
they're not very subjective, you know,

1133
00:57:14,019 --> 00:57:15,160
they're not very collaborative.

1134
00:57:16,477 --> 00:57:19,098
Detailing is high poly, it's super skilled,

1135
00:57:19,658 --> 00:57:20,599
and it's definitely fun,

1136
00:57:21,279 --> 00:57:22,620
and it's definitely something our artists

1137
00:57:22,640 --> 00:57:23,761
are perfectly capable of doing,

1138
00:57:24,481 --> 00:57:26,442
but it's not necessarily the most impactful part

1139
00:57:26,462 --> 00:57:28,964
of the production, and by not doing this,

1140
00:57:29,044 --> 00:57:31,065
it frees them up to do some other more important things,

1141
00:57:31,105 --> 00:57:32,246
which I'll talk about in a second.

1142
00:57:32,906 --> 00:57:34,407
But just to kind of wrap up,

1143
00:57:34,427 --> 00:57:35,688
what did we outsource in total?

1144
00:57:36,588 --> 00:57:36,968
Quite a lot.

1145
00:57:38,232 --> 00:57:41,213
So using man hours spent on the asset as a metric

1146
00:57:41,754 --> 00:57:43,555
for almost 90% of our content,

1147
00:57:44,315 --> 00:57:46,076
one of our partners did the majority

1148
00:57:46,096 --> 00:57:47,297
of the actual asset creation.

1149
00:57:47,317 --> 00:57:48,718
You know, they spent more time on it than we did.

1150
00:57:49,358 --> 00:57:50,899
That doesn't mean that they did all of it

1151
00:57:51,399 --> 00:57:53,841
because we still have our fingers in every single character.

1152
00:57:53,881 --> 00:57:54,941
We're still keeping ownership

1153
00:57:54,961 --> 00:57:56,442
of those identity-defining parts,

1154
00:57:57,223 --> 00:57:59,504
but it did mean that they spent more time on it than we did.

1155
00:58:01,069 --> 00:58:06,994
But for 99% of all characters, at some point in their life cycle we had some kind of external

1156
00:58:07,014 --> 00:58:08,095
development assistance.

1157
00:58:08,616 --> 00:58:12,900
So even if a character is owned internally, like one of our lead cast, we still get a

1158
00:58:12,940 --> 00:58:16,764
partner to do at least some of the more mechanical, less collaborative bits like UVs or baking

1159
00:58:16,784 --> 00:58:17,144
or LOLs.

1160
00:58:18,325 --> 00:58:28,250
And just a reminder, I said the internal team only did about 13%, which doesn't really sound like a lot, but it's 13% of our enormous scope, so that's a pretty impressive chunk of work.

1161
00:58:29,071 --> 00:58:31,452
And it was pretty awesome work, so I'm just going to take a sec to show it off.

1162
00:58:33,013 --> 00:58:41,718
Internally, we made pretty much the same amount of characters as a Killzone game, so outsourcing more didn't mean that we did less, it just meant that we outsourced more.

1163
00:58:42,578 --> 00:58:46,680
And through outsourcing more, we gave the game the scope of content it needed to be a success.

1164
00:58:48,398 --> 00:58:49,999
So how can you decide what to outsource?

1165
00:58:50,019 --> 00:58:51,260
Well, make a habit of asking yourself

1166
00:58:51,320 --> 00:58:52,400
if something can be outsourced,

1167
00:58:52,421 --> 00:58:53,982
because the answer is yes, but often you think.

1168
00:58:54,882 --> 00:58:56,883
The more collaborative, the more subjective something is,

1169
00:58:56,903 --> 00:58:58,264
the more difficult it is to outsource.

1170
00:58:58,805 --> 00:59:01,166
So work out where your team really needs to add the value

1171
00:59:01,486 --> 00:59:02,847
and hold on to those things in particular.

1172
00:59:03,808 --> 00:59:06,430
These things, they tend to be less content creation

1173
00:59:06,930 --> 00:59:08,011
and more problem solving.

1174
00:59:09,532 --> 00:59:11,293
See, our internal team, they focus more

1175
00:59:11,313 --> 00:59:13,134
on that problem solving, collaborative aspect,

1176
00:59:13,514 --> 00:59:14,935
and then delegate to the larger part

1177
00:59:14,955 --> 00:59:16,676
of the actual content creation to our partners.

1178
00:59:17,940 --> 00:59:20,421
This leads into what I look for in a team member.

1179
00:59:21,041 --> 00:59:23,983
You see, in my experience, you can categorize game artists

1180
00:59:24,003 --> 00:59:25,303
into one or two boxes.

1181
00:59:25,904 --> 00:59:27,685
You have the artists who are focused

1182
00:59:27,725 --> 00:59:29,806
on making great pieces of work, you know, the craftsmen.

1183
00:59:30,326 --> 00:59:32,027
And there are artists who love figuring stuff out

1184
00:59:32,067 --> 00:59:33,868
and pushing the boundaries, you know, the tinkerers.

1185
00:59:34,963 --> 00:59:39,888
And the people in that first category, they have ownership needs which are pretty focused.

1186
00:59:39,908 --> 00:59:43,692
They put their all into that one thing they're doing now, that thing is theirs.

1187
00:59:44,533 --> 00:59:48,997
And we have a need for people with this focus, but it's not always a very collaborative approach.

1188
00:59:49,457 --> 00:59:52,901
So I found these guys, more often than not, can work just as well remotely.

1189
00:59:54,304 --> 00:59:59,650
When it comes to the team who are inside the studio, I want the mad scientists, okay?

1190
01:00:00,131 --> 01:00:04,996
These guys are the ones who are at the cutting edge of what the tech and what the tools can do.

1191
01:00:05,477 --> 01:00:08,080
These guys are the first people to get out of their chair and collaborate.

1192
01:00:08,820 --> 01:00:12,765
And these guys are the ones who are just like trying out all kinds of crazy shit on their own initiative.

1193
01:00:13,605 --> 01:00:16,426
So when it comes to ownership, you know, these guys say they think bigger

1194
01:00:16,446 --> 01:00:22,708
Yeah, they own big broad problems like human anatomy and deformation or digital tailoring

